STIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/C2C5C34F-DEBE-4165-82B3-F7C025496C5B"><gtr:id>C2C5C34F-DEBE-4165-82B3-F7C025496C5B</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Christopher</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>James</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Chapman</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH002413%2F1"><gtr:id>65E89444-3D22-43A0-946B-FA37764F8DC9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Challenging the orthodoxy of school effectiveness and school improvement: Towards new theoretical perspectives</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H002413/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This seminar series is builds on findings from the BERA Educational Effectiveness and Improvement SIG suggesting traditional understandings of school effectiveness and improvement (based on narrow cognitive student outcome measures) have become less relevant as systems have attempted to adapt to a complex range of emerging agendas.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This leads us to argue new theoretical perspectives are required which move beyond considering effectiveness and improvement in terms of 'schools' and 'cognitive student outcomes' (even when weighted to account for background factors) to 'education' and a 'broader set of outcomes'. This shift requires a rethink of how effectiveness and improvement have been understood by the field, and constructed by policy makers and practitioners.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;The aim of the series is to explore two key issues:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>attention must be given to promoting equity as well as effectiveness. In recent times, the quasi-market has often meant one school or student's gain is another's loss and that patterns of effectiveness have tended to mirror social inequities&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the field must develop new methodologies if a) inequities are to be challenged and, b) if a broader set of outcome measures are to be developed. &lt;/li>

&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>Therefore the findings from this series will address two overarching questions:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>How can educational effectiveness and improvement research and practice support the development of a more equitable education service?&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>What are the key indicators of educational effectiveness and improvement and what are the new methodologies required to facilitate a shift from 'school' effectiveness and improvement to 'educational' effectiveness and improvement?

  &lt;ul>
   

   &lt;li>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li>

  &lt;/ul>
&lt;/li>

